    <table>
      <caption>Solo Drills</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Technical Standup</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Arm posted behind you at 45 degrees (matching the force vector),
                leaving enough space to move your hips back
              </li>
              <li>Rear hip and knee on the mat</li>
              <li>
                Torso bladed toward the opponent (squaring your torso will make
                your non-posting shoulder a potential lever)
              </li>
              <li>
                Front arm maintaining knee-elbow connection but also free for
                defense
              </li>
              <li>
                Front leg tucked in (leaving it out makes it light and a
                potential lever)
              </li>
              <li>Strong posture, head up</li>
              <li>
                To move backward, lift your hip and slide your rear knee to your
                posted hand, replacing it as you switch to a track stance
                (scooting backward will leave your front leg out and vulnerable
                as a lever)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Bridge</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Face your opponent’s force vector (e.g., a 45-degree angle when
                in bottom side control)
              </li>
              <li>
                Tuck your feet into your butt and stay on the balls of your feet
              </li>
              <li>
                Raise your feet slightly and then drive them explosively into
                the ground to bridge (plyometric rebound)
              </li>
              <li>When bridging at an angle, bridge onto your shoulder</li>
              <li>Maintain hip-shoulder alignment</li>
              <li>
                If you slide backward, bring your feet back under you to
                maintain your force production
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Hip Escape</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                After a 45-degree bridge on two legs: stay tightly tucked and
                bring your butt backward while maintaining knee-elbow connection
              </li>
              <li>
                Small hip escape: post and push with your top leg as you bring
                your bottom knee in to create knee-elbow connection
              </li>
              <li>
                With partial inversion: post and push with your top leg to make
                space to bring your bottom knee in and recompose your guard
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Inversion and Half Granby</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Use frames (e.g., feet on hips, straight arm on knee) throughout
                the movement to maintain distance between you and your opponent
              </li>
              <li>
                Your head and neck don’t touch the mat (you’re on your
                shoulders)
              </li>
              <li>
                As you invert, step onto the mat with your top foot, bringing it
                far away from your opponent (so they can’t control your leg)
              </li>
              <li>
                As you invert, maintain knee-elbow connection by bringing your
                bottom knee in
              </li>
              <li>
                Solid structure will allow you to support weight (e.g., your
                opponent pushing into you) on your spine while you’re inverted
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Hip Heist</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>Start on all fours (knees and elbows)</li>
              <li>
                Post onto a hand and the opposite leg, then lift your hips as
                you step far and shoot your hips forward
              </li>
              <li>
                Maintain strong frames and posture (hips up, head up, posting on
                straight arm or elbow)
              </li>
              <li>
                “Peek out” and then turn in (push off your rear foot and turn
                onto your forward knee as you turn to face the opposite
                direction)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td></tr
        >

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Hip Switch</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Start with one hip on the ground (body bladed toward the
                ground), posting on your bottom arm
              </li>
              <li>
                Post your top elbow as you rotate and cut your opposite hip to
                the floor
              </li>
              <li>
                Alternatively, face the ground with both arms posted and
                alternate your grounded hip (can combine with a windshield wiper
                motion)
              </li>
              <li>Useful for shedding frames and hooks</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Windshield Wiper</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Useful for passing over a limb and shedding hooks, frames, and
                clamps
              </li>
              <li>
                Curl your heel toward your butt while shifting your weight and
                turning your leg over the top of something (e.g., post on your
                hands, bring your knee to the ground, and staple your opponent’s
                limb as you pivot over it)
              </li>
              <li>Can be done with one leg or both</li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Backstep</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Backstep: Post on the ball of one foot and the same-side hand,
                then step back with the other leg as you turn your hips over
              </li>
              <li>
                Long step: Post on one knee and the same-side elbow, then step
                back with the other leg as you turn your hips over (like a
                scorpion kick)
              </li>
              <li>
                After stepping back, keep your center of gravity between your
                posts to maintain base (stop your movement before you
                over-rotate)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Rolls</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>Head and neck don’t touch the ground</li>
              <li>
                Forward roll: start with one knee up, land with your
                rolling-side knee up and the other knee tucked in flat on the
                mat, and then get up into a track stance (similar to a technical
                standup)
              </li>
              <li>
                Backward roll: far leg (rolling-side leg) stays compact
                (providing an immediate base as it lands), near leg extends a
                bit so you can land in a ready, force-producing stance
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Eggbeater</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                To shed grips on your shins, rotate your lower legs (if your
                opponent is exerting downward force on your legs, purely
                vertical movement will be ineffective) while grip fighting with
                your hands
              </li>
              <li>
                Most effective when your legs are bent at a 90-degree angle
                (more difficult once your opponent has pushed them down to 45
                degrees)
              </li>
              <li>
                Switch your hips throughout the movement to increase your range
                of motion
              </li>
              <li>
                Rotate your lower legs in opposing directions, switching between
                outward and inward
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Shin Circle</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                To shed a hook on your leg, rotate your knee inward while
                driving it down and kicking yourself in the butt, then rotate
                the knee back out and drive your foot to the mat
              </li>
              <li>
                Keep the circling leg heavy throughout the movement (if you make
                it light, it will be a lever for your opponent)
              </li>
              <li>
                Keep your center of gravity above your circling knee (don’t
                shift it forward past your base)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <table>
      <caption>Grip Fighting - Gi</caption>

      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
          <th scope="col">Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th scope="row">General</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>A grip should enhance your level of control</li>
              <li>
                Grip as close to a lever point (a joint or the end of the lever)
                as possible (e.g., top of the spine, wrist, elbow, knee)
              </li>
              <li>
                To maximize control, roll and rotate (do both when possible) the
                gripped material and remove slack (e.g., when gripping a sleeve,
                roll your hand to your knuckles and frame it against your
                opponent’s wrist)
              </li>
              <li>
                Rolling and rotating the material forces your opponent to break
                alignment (due to needing to address multiple directions) when
                attempting to break a grip
              </li>
              <li>
                Be prepared to release the grip and regrip if your opponent is
                breaking your grip
              </li>
              <li>
                Grip levels: benign, dangerous (providing control of a lever or
                the ability to effectively push and pull), and deadly (leading
                to a choke)
              </li>
              <li>
                Strategically, you can start with a benign grip and convert it
                into a better one
              </li>
            </ul>

            <ul>
              <li>
                To break a grip: break the structure of the gripping limb, then
                take the material in the direction where there is a gap
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Collar Grip</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Ideally, at the collarbone rather than at the pec (uncomfortable
                for your opponent to drive into, threatens a choke, more
                material control and body leverage)
              </li>
              <li>
                Roll the material into your fingers and rotate your palm up
              </li>
            </ul>

            Same-side collar grip
            <ul>
              <li>
                Generally not useful by itself (not much rotational control or
                offensive potential)—better when complemented with opposite
                sleeve control and/or a guard
              </li>
              <li>
                Useful for posture control (e.g., pulling your opponent down in
                closed guard)
              </li>
              <li>
                Useful when passing (e.g., offers rotational control during a
                knee cut)
              </li>
              <li>
                Generally, same-side collar grip is superior to cross-collar
                when on top (when you’re more mobile and able to change angles)
              </li>
            </ul>

            Cross-collar grip
            <ul>
              <li>
                Useful for pulling your opponent across (using a rowing motion
                to create a dominant angle and expose their back)—offers more
                rotational control and offensive potential than the same-side
                collar grip
              </li>
            </ul>

            Grip breaks
            <ul>
              <li>
                Prevention: push the elbow to redirect your opponent’s arm as
                they reach
              </li>
              <li>
                Back away until your opponent’s arm is straight, then push their
                elbow up using a Y-block with one or both of your hands (FOR
                SAFETY, don’t pop the elbow up if your opponent isn’t aware of
                what’s happening)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <th scope="row">Sleeve Grip</th>
          <td
            ><ul>
              <li>
                Cuff grip: roll the sleeve into your fingers and twist outward,
                removing slack and framing your fist against your opponent’s
                forearm

                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Faster to attain than the pistol grip and more popular in
                    general
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>
                Pistol grip: hook the sleeve with your index finger, then gather
                a fistful of material, removing as much slack as possible and
                leaving your thumb out for safety—twist your fist to block your
                opponent’s arm with your ulnar bone (make your wrists
                perpendicular)

                <ul>
                  <li>Superior to cuff grip in removing slack</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>

            Mirror sleeve grip
            <ul>
              <li>
                Useful for moving your opponent’s arm away from their body
              </li>
              <li>Useful for pinning your opponent’s hand to their body</li>
              <li>
                Useful for controlling your opponent’s arm in general (prevent
                them from posting, set up an arm drag, etc.)—strong,
                end-of-lever control
              </li>
              <li>
                Limited control when used by itself—better when combined with a
                hinge on your opponent (e.g., foot on their hip, foot on their
                bicep)
              </li>
            </ul>

            Cross-sleeve grip
            <ul>
              <li>
                Useful for pulling your opponent’s arm across their body and
                exposing their back—if using a cuff grip, you can allow for more
                initial slack in the material so you can rotate the grip to the
                other side of your opponent’s wrist and then pull their arm
                across
              </li>
              <li>
                Can be useful for defense through pushing your opponent’s arm
                away from their body, but you must turn and maintain
                hip-shoulder alignment (don’t just pass your arm over your
                centerline)
              </li>
            </ul>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>

