      <table>
        <caption>Phases of Guard</caption>

        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col" style="width: 120px"></th>
            <th scope="col">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>

        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Engagement</th>
            <td>
              In seated guard:
              <ul>
                <li>Don’t reach your arms out</li>
                <li>
                  Grab the closest part of your opponent (e.g., their
                  fingers)—if you reach for their sleeve, they’ll be able to
                  grip you
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use your grips on their hands to clear the way so you can grip
                  their collar, the back of their head, or their arm 2-on-1
                </li>
                <li>
                  Grip progression: fingers → sleeve or wrist (lever to
                  shoulder) → collar or head (lever to torso)
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your opponent is able to grip you, grip-match them (don’t
                  let them grip you for free, battle for an advantage)
                </li>
              </ul></td
            >
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Maintenance</th>
            <td>
              In seated guard:
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Block your opponent’s leading edge (the knee if they’re
                  standing and circling you) with your hand, post with your
                  other hand, and continually adjust your angle to face your
                  opponent, switching your hips and the framing arm when
                  necessary
                </li>
                <li>
                  From here, you can pull to another guard (e.g., shin-to-shin,
                  De La Riva, tripod)
                </li>
              </ul>
            </td>
          </tr>

          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Retention</th>
            <td>
              In seated guard:
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If your opponent is in front of you and their knee starts
                  collapsing your straight arm (turning your frame into a
                  lever), shorten it to an elbow frame to turn the lever back
                  into a frame
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your opponent has a dominant angle and their knee starts
                  collapsing your straight arm, don’t turn to face them (turning
                  in will give up the guard pass)
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Half Granby: As your blocking frame starts collapsing,
                      collapse your posting arm (arm frame → elbow frame →
                      shoulder frame) and put your shoulder to the mat so that
                      you’re lying sideways and turned away from your opponent,
                      giving your framing arm room to straighten.
                    </li>
                    <li>Hip escape:</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Frame against the leading edge (often the knee/shin or
                  shoulder/upper arm), then mobilize your hips to reset your
                  angle
                </li>
                <li>
                  If your hips get turned, maintain posture by turning your
                  torso to match
                </li>
              </ul>

              In recumbent guard:
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use knee-elbow connection to prevent guard passes (adjust your
                  elbow placement based on the situation—e.g., protecting
                  against a knee wedge versus an underhook)
                </li>
              </ul>
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

